SUMMARIZER="F">     

The magnitude 6.9 earthquake which struck 75 miles south of San
Francisco occurred in a region targeted by seismologists as having the
highest probability of a strong quake in Northern California.  The US
Geologic Survey last year gave a 30% chance for a strong quake in the
Santa Cruz mountains by the year 2018.  Initial reports indicated
widespread damage to highways and old masonry buildings.  The USGS
says the highest probability for a California earthquake of high
magnitude is in the town of Parkfield, where they give a 90% chance
for a magnitude 6 earthquake by the year 2018.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d57"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891028-0022"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="F">    

An earthquake of magnitude 7.2 shook the Solomon Islands today (28
October) the USGS reported.  It was the largest there since 7.4 quake
in 1978.  There were no immediate reports or injury or damage, but
quakes in that area usually don't cause much because it is sparsely
populated and not developed.  No Pacific-wide tsunami was generated by
the quake.  Earlier in the year, an 8.3 quake hit the Macquarie
Islands south of Australia.  A 7 magnitude earthquake is considered
major and is capable of heavy damage.  A magnitude 8 quake is a
"great" quake capable of tremendous damage.</SUM>

<SUM
